## 11. Voice/Video Calls (WebRTC)

### Architecture

Introvert uses **flutter_webrtc** for native AV capture/playback and **libp2p** for signaling relay.

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│                    Call Architecture                  │
│                                                      │
│  ┌──────────────┐  SDP/ICE   ┌──────────────┐      │
│  │ flutter_webrtc│◄─────────►│  Rust (FFI)   │      │
│  │ (Dart)        │           │  libp2p mesh   │      │
│  └──────┬───────┘           └──────┬───────┘      │
│         │                          │               │
│         │ Local AV                 │ Signaling      │
│         ▼                          ▼               │
│  ┌──────────────┐           ┌──────────────┐      │
│  │  Camera/Mic  │           │  RBN Relay   │      │
│  │  Speaker     │           │  (if needed) │      │
│  └──────────────┘           └──────────────┘      │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
```

### 1:1 Call Flow

```
Caller                                Callee
  │                                     │
  │  1. Check network quality           │
  │  2. Create WebRTC PeerConnection    │
  │  3. Acquire local media (camera/mic)│
  │  4. Create SDP Offer                │
  │  5. Send WebRtcNative signal        │
  │────────────────────────────────────►│
  │                                     │  6. Event 14: Incoming call
  │                                     │  7. Show incoming call overlay
  │                                     │  8. User accepts
  │                                     │  9. Create PeerConnection
  │                                     │ 10. Acquire local media
  │                                     │ 11. Set remote description (offer)
  │                                     │ 12. Create SDP Answer
  │◄────────────────────────────────────│ 13. Send WebRtcNative signal
  │ 14. Set remote description (answer)│
  │                                     │
  │  15. ICE candidate exchange         │
  │◄───────────────────────────────────►│
  │                                     │
  │  16. ICE connected                  │
  │  17. Start quality monitoring       │
  │  18. Call active                    │
```

### Group Call Flow (Full Mesh)

```
Initiator                Participant B         Participant C
  │                         │                     │
  │  1. Create call_id      │                     │
  │  2. Send GROUP_CALL_INVITE│                    │
  │────────────────────────►│                     │
  │─────────────────────────────────────────────────►│
  │                         │                     │
  │  3. Initiate WebRTC     │                     │
  │     to each participant │                     │
  │◄───────────────────────►│                     │
  │◄──────────────────────────────────────────────►│
  │                         │                     │
  │  4. All connected       │                     │
  │  5. Grid view displayed │                     │
```

### Call Quality Monitoring

| Quality Level | Bitrate | Packet Loss | RTT | Action |
|--------------|---------|-------------|-----|--------|
| Excellent | > 1000 kbps | < 5% | < 500ms | Full video |
| Good | 300-1000 kbps | < 5% | < 500ms | Video OK |
| Fair | 100-300 kbps | < 5% | < 500ms | Low quality video |
| Poor | 40-100 kbps | < 15% | < 1000ms | Auto-switch to audio |
| Critical | < 40 kbps | > 15% | > 1000ms | Terminate call |

### Adaptive Quality

- Pre-call network check blocks calls if bandwidth < 40 kbps
- During call, auto-downgrades video→audio when quality drops
- Shows "AUDIO ONLY" indicator when downgraded
- Notifies remote peer of quality change via `quality_downgrade` signal

### Group Call Limits

- Maximum **8 participants** per group call
- Call button hidden when group has > 8 members
- Safety checks at all entry points (initiate, join, accept)

---

## 12. Group Mesh (Gossipsub)

### Protocol

- **Gossipsub v1.2.0** for message propagation
- Custom topic per group: `group_{group_id}`
- Signed messages with Ed25519 keys

### Group Message Flow

```
Member A                Gossipsub               Member B
  │                         │                     │
  │  1. Sign GroupMessage   │                     │
  │  2. Publish to topic    │                     │
  │────────────────────────►│  3. Propagate       │
  │                         │────────────────────►│
  │                         │                     │  4. Verify signature
  │                         │                     │  5. Decrypt with group key
  │                         │                     │  6. Store locally
```

### Group Actions

| Action | Permission | Description |
|--------|-----------|-------------|
| `Message` | Member+ | Send text message |
| `AddMember` | Admin+ | Add new member |
| `RemoveMember` | Admin+ | Remove member |
| `UpdateRole` | Creator | Change member role |
| `DeleteGroup` | Creator | Delete group entirely |
| `Reaction` | Member+ | Emoji reaction |
| `SetRetention` | Admin+ | Message lifetime |
| `DeleteMessage` | Owner/Admin | Delete specific message |
| `EditMessage` | Owner | Edit message content |
| `MuteMember` | Admin+ | Mute a member |
| `UnmuteMember` | Admin+ | Unmute a member |

### Role Hierarchy

1. **Creator** — Full control, can delete group
2. **Admin** — Manage members, messages, settings
3. **Member** — Send messages, reactions, self-remove

### Group File Transfers

- Files sent via Gossipsub manifest broadcast
- Each member pulls chunks directly from seeders (Sovereign Swarm)
- Completed peers register as additional seeders
- Dynamic seeder discovery via Kademlia `FindProviders` every 5 seconds

---

## 13. Read Receipts & Delivery Confirmation

### Status Values

| Value | Status | Meaning |
|-------|--------|---------|
| 0 | Sent | Message sent from local device |
| 1 | Delivered | Message received by remote peer |
| 2 | Read | Message viewed by remote peer |

### 1:1 Read Receipt Flow

```
Sender                                    Receiver
  │                                          │
  │  Status: 0 (Sent)                        │
  │  ────────────────────────────────────────►│
  │                                          │  Rust: Store message
  │                                          │  Rust: Send Ack {status: 1}
  │◄─────────────────────────────────────────│
  │  Status: 1 (Delivered) → ✓✓             │
  │                                          │
  │         ... User opens chat ...          │
  │                                          │
  │                                          │  Dart: _markMessagesAsRead()
  │                                          │  Dart: sendAcknowledgement(status: 2)
  │◄─────────────────────────────────────────│
  │  Status: 2 (Read) → ✓✓ blue            │
```

### Read Receipt Implementation

**Receiver side (chat_screen.dart):**
```dart
void _markMessagesAsRead() {
  // Update local DB
  _client.updateMessageStatusForPeer(widget.peerId, 0);
  // Send read receipts to remote peer
  final raw = _client.getMessages(widget.peerId);
  for (var m in raw) {
    final isMe = m['is_me'] == true;
    final msgId = m['msg_id'] as String?;
    final status = m['status'] as int? ?? 1;
    if (!isMe && msgId != null && status != 0) {
      _client.sendAcknowledgement(widget.peerId, msgId, 2);
    }
  }
}
```

**Sender side (Event 13 handler):**
```dart
// Rust dispatches Event 13: [status_byte][msg_id_bytes]
final status = event.data[0];
final mid = utf8.decode(event.data.sublist(1));
// Update message status in UI
_messages[idx].status = status;
```

### Group Read Receipts

- Group messages track unread counts per group
- `updateGroupMessageStatus(groupId, 0)` marks all as read locally
- Read receipts sent for each unread incoming message
- Unread badge shown on chat list

---

## 14. Performance Specifications

### Connection Type Performance

| Connection Type | Speed | Latency | Chunk Size | Pipeline | Use Case |
|----------------|-------|---------|------------|----------|----------|
| **Direct P2P** | **50 Mbps** | 5-50ms | 256 KB | 8-deep | Same network, hole-punched |
| **Group Swarm (LAN)** | **50 Mbps** | 5-30ms | 64 KB | 8-deep @ 10ms | Group files on same LAN |
| **Relayed QUIC** | **2 Mbps** | 30-150ms | 64 KB | 4-deep @ 50ms | Cross-network via RBN |
| **Relayed TCP** | **0.5-3 Mbps** | 50-250ms | 64 KB | 4-deep | UDP-blocked networks |
| **Mesh Mailbox** | Throttled | Async | 64 KB | Queue | Offline store-and-forward |

### Direct P2P (50 Mbps)

- **How established:** Dynamic STUN/TURN hole punching or same LAN
- **Transport:** libp2p QUIC (UDP) or TCP on port 443
- **Chunk strategy:** 256 KB sequential push chunks, 8-deep pipeline
- **No relay overhead:** Direct device-to-device communication
- **Auto-upgrade:** Relay connections upgrade to direct when addresses discovered
- **File transfer:** Full bandwidth saturation on local networks

### Cross-Network / Relayed (2 Mbps)

- **How established:** Through RBN circuit relay
- **Transport:** Circuit relay v2 over QUIC or TCP on port 443
- **Chunk strategy:** 64 KB pipelined pull chunks, 4-deep sliding window
- **Pacing:** 50ms between requests to prevent relay flooding
- **Flow control:** Per-peer concurrency limits prevent socket saturation
- **Bandwidth sharing:** Multiple transfers share available relay bandwidth

### Messaging Latency

| Scenario | Expected Latency |
|----------|-----------------|
| Same LAN (direct) | 5-50ms |
| Cross-city (direct) | 20-100ms |
| Cross-country (direct) | 50-200ms |
| Via relay (QUIC) | 100-300ms |
| Via relay (TCP) | 200-500ms |
| Mailbox delivery | 5s - 15min (poll interval) |

### Mailbox Performance

| State | Poll Interval | Throughput |
|-------|--------------|------------|
| Active foreground | 5 seconds | Immediate drain |
| Background | 15 minutes | Batch drain |
| On reconnect | Immediate | Full drain |

